Stock Price Prediction and Portfolio Optimization¶

Objective: Goal of this project is to develop a machine learning strategy to maximize the gains by implementing reinforcement learning algorithm. First part of the project implements strategy to optimize the portfolio and in the second part Q learning algorithm is implemented to predict the stock movement based on which uy or sell decision is taken.

Technical indicator are identified to generate a rule based manual strategy and then performance of the machine learning strategy is compared with manual rule based strategy with the help of market simulator.

1 Portfolio Optimization¶

1.1 Dataset¶

For each stock typically stock data is available in CSV format with columns -

Date, Open, High, Low, Close, Volume, Adj Close

Note that Close column is the actual price that was reported at the exchange when the stock closed for that day and Adjusted Close is the adjusted price due to events such as stock splits and dividend payments etc. We use pandas dataframe in order to process this stock data in python.

Pandas functions df.dropna() is used to remove rows with NaN values and df.dropna(subset=COLNAME) is used to remove rows with NaN values in specified column

We also use df.join to combine data from two stocks into a single dataframe. df.join(otherdf, how=inner) executes the inner join, only includes data where both exist in df and other df. It also eliminates all the bad dates when stock market is closed.

1.1 Statistical Analysis of Time Series¶

Rolling Statistics: A Bollinger Band is a technical analysis tool defined by a set of lines plotted two standard deviations (positively and negatively) away from a simple moving average (SMA) of the security's price, but can be adjusted to user preferences. Bollinger Bands were developed and copyrighted by famous technical trader John Bollinger.

Daily Return: Daily return is the profit/loss made by the stock compared to the previous day.

Cumulative Return: While daily returns are useful, it doesn't give immediate insight into the gains he had made till date, especially if the stock is very volatile. Cumulative return is computed relative to the day investment is made. If cumulative return is above one, you are making profits else you are in loss.

In [3]:

lower_band = rm_SPY - rstd_SPY*2

1.3 Histogram of Daily Returns¶

Kurtosis tells us about the tails of a distribution. If we assume that our histogram is similar to a gaussian Distribution or normal distribution, then the measure of Kurtosis tells us how different our histogram is from that of the traditional distribution.
If we measure a positive Kurtosis (fat tails) it means that there are more occurrences out in these tails than there are in the normal distribution.
 If we measure a negative Kurtosis (skinny tails) it means that there are fewer occurrences out in these tails than there are in the normal distribution

Volatility is measured by the standard deviation of daily returns displayed using Histogram. Volatile stocks have return distributions that are very spread out. By contrast, low volatility stocks have tight distributions, where the daily returns are clustered around the average.

Scatter Plots: (the daily returns of that stock with respect to SPY) Beta - how reactive is the stock to the market. If the slope (Beta) is 1 it means that if the market goes up 1%, that stock also goes up 1%. If beta is 2, if the market goes up 1%, the stock goes up 2%. Alpha - That stock on average is performing a little bit better than the S&P500 (SPY) every day if Alpha is positive. If its negative it means its returned a little less than the market overall.

The slope (Beta) is not Correlation! Correlation is how tightly these individual points fit that line. So you could have a shallow slope with a higher correlation, or you can have a steeper slope and the data fitting the line at a higher correlation.

1.4 Portfolio Statistics¶

To assess the performance of portfolio following statistics are tracked -

  • Cumulative return
  • Average period return (if sampling frequency == 252 then this is average daily return)
  • Standard deviation of daily returns
  • Sharpe ratio of the overall portfolio, given daily risk free rate (usually 0), and yearly sampling frequency (usually 252, the no. of trading days in a year)
  • Ending value of the portfolio

1.5 Portfolio Optimization¶

The simplest way to optimize the portfolio is to compare Cumulative return of stocks that maximized return over that time period. The allocation would be 100% to the highest returning stock.

But if you want to optimize for minimum volatility or Sharpe ratio you have to evaluate various combinations of those stocks. In order to use an optimizer that minimizes we need to do the following:

  • Provide a function to minimize f(x)
  • Provide an initial guess for x
  • Call the optimizer
  • And we want the optimizer to try different allocations to discover the best set of allocations that optimizes this function
  • We want to optimize for Sharpe ratio, but f(x) is not the actual Sharpe ratio value, we want to optimize for -1 * the largest Sharpe ratio because the available optimizer function is minimize
  • This will find the best allocation or the best value for x to solve this problem
  • x can have multiple dimensions and each of the dimensions is the percentage of funds to allocate to each of those stocks
In [7]:
#Function to optimize
def get_negative_sharpe_ratio(allocs, prices, sv=1000000, rfr=0.0, sf=252):
    # Get daily portfolio value
    # Normalize the prices according to the first day
    norm_prices = prices/prices.iloc[0,:]

    # Compute prices based on the allocations
    alloc_prices = norm_prices * allocs

    # Calculate position values
    pos_vals = alloc_prices * sv

    # Get daily portfolio value
    port_val = pos_vals.sum(axis=1).to_frame()
    port_val.columns = ["port_val"]

    # Get portfolio statistics
    cr = port_val.iloc[-1, 0]/port_val.iloc[0, 0] - 1

    #Compute daily returns
    daily_returns = port_val.pct_change()
    daily_returns.iloc[0,:] = 0
    daily_returns = daily_returns[1:]

    adr = daily_returns["port_val"].mean()
    sddr = daily_returns["port_val"].std()
    sr = np.sqrt(sample_freq) * (adr - risk_free_rate) / sddr
    neg_sr = sr * (-1)

    return neg_sr

bounds = ((0,1),(0,1),(0,1),(0,1))

constraints = ({'type': 'eq', 'fun': lambda x:  np.sum(x)-1.0})

initial_guess = np.ones((len(['GOOG', 'IBM', 'GLD', 'AAPL'])), dtype=np.float32)/(len(['GOOG', 'IBM', 'GLD', 'AAPL']))

result = spo.minimize(get_negative_sharpe_ratio, initial_guess, args=(prices,), method='SLSQP', constraints=constraints, bounds=bounds)
allocs = result.x

norm_prices = prices/prices.iloc[0,:]

# Compute prices based on the allocations
alloc_prices = norm_prices * allocs

# Calculate position values

Choosing a portfolio from among the enormous range of assets now available to an investor would be facilitated if we could locate the return risk ratio of a particular allocation along a spectrum of possibilities. A comparison between portfolio choices can tell us, for example, whether it is better to select a suboptimal portfolio from a large class of assets or to perform a Markowitz optimal procedure on a subset of the assets. A common criterion for this assessment is the expected return-to-risk tradeoff as measured by the Sharpe ratio.

2.1 Technical Indicators¶

Technical indicators are a fundamental part of technical analysis and are typically plotted as a chart pattern to try to predict the market trend. Indicators generally overlay on price chart data to indicate where the price is going, or whether the price is in an "overbought" condition or an "oversold" condition.

Trading strategy is built upon following three technical indicators which helps in making buy, sell or do-nothing decisions.

2.1.1 Simple Moving Average¶

Simple moving average (SMA) smooths out past price data. It calculates the rolling mean price of a stock for specified lookback periods. It is used in many different technical indicators and it can also serve as a stand-alone indicator for analyzing price movement.

As SMA smooths out the noise in the stock prices and generate buy or sell signals by identifying trend direction. SMA serves as the support line for stock price. If stock prices move significantly from SMA, price tends to come back to SMA. Strategy is to buy stock when stock price falls significantly below the SMA and to short the stock when stock price rise significantly above SMA.

In order to capture this indicator, we calculate the ration of price to SMA and buy stock when price to SMA ratio is below threshold and buy stock when price to SMA ratio is above threshold. Below graph was plotted for JPM stock for look back window of 20 days.

In [9]:

2.1.2 Bollinger Bands¶

This indicator expands on the Simple Moving Average (SMA) by including standard deviation of prices from the SMA. Bollinger Bands detects the volatility and dynamics of the price movement in the stock price. Using Bollinger Bands, we can predict whether current trend in the stock price will continue or turn around.

Central line in the Bollinger bands represents the Simple Moving Average (SMA). Upper and lower lines of band represent the + and - 2 standard deviations of stock price from the SMA respectively.
When stock price fluctuates highly, gap between upper and lower bands is largest. Gap is lowest when prices fluctuation is less. If the price is close to or outside of the upper band, the stock price would be considered high and investor should sell the stock. On the other hand, if the price is near the lower band, stock price would be considered low and investor should buy the stock.

Bollinger Band Percentage (%B) is calculated by subtracting the lower band from the price and then dividing it by the difference between upper and lower bands. This BBP is thus less than zero when the price falls below the lower band and is greater than 1 when the price rises above the upper band. The Bollinger Band family is plotted on the same stock data.

  • Middle Band = SMA with look back window of 20 days
  • Upper Band = SMA + (2 x standard deviation of price)
  • Lower Band = SMA - (2 x standard deviation of price)
  • %B = (Current Price - Lower Band) / (Upper Band - Lower Band)

2.1.3 Momentum¶

This technical indicator help investor to predict strength of a price movement. Momentum is calculated by comparing the most recent closing price to a previous closing price over the lookback window. Below chart displays the momentum indicator as a single line and a separate stock price line for JPM is also shown in the chart.

M = CP CPn

Where M is momentum, CP is closing price and n is lookback window. If the current price is higher than the price in the past, then the Momentum is positive. On the other hand, if the current price is lower than the price in the past, then the Momentum is negative. When the Momentum crosses above the zero-line stock price is reversing and price is bottomed out hence it is a buy signal. When the Momentum crosses below the zero-line stock price is reversing and price is topped out hence it is a sell signal.

2.3 Theoretically Optimal Strategy¶

Assuming we can peek into future but constrained by the portfolio size and order limits we create a set of trades that represents the best a strategy could possibly do during the in sample period. Objective is to identify the upper bound on performance. We will use adjusted close prices with the market simulator.

In [13]:
#Calulate Theoratically Optimal Portfolio 
trades = []
holdlimit = 0
for i in range(len(prices)-1):
    # print(holdlimit)
    if prices.ix[i,'AAPL'] < prices.ix[i + 1,'AAPL']:
        if holdlimit == 0:
            holdlimit += 1000
            trades.append([prices.index[i], +1000])
        elif holdlimit == 1000:
            trades.append([prices.index[i], 0])
        else:
            holdlimit += 2000
            trades.append([prices.index[i], +2000])
    elif prices.ix[i,'AAPL'] > prices.ix[i + 1,'AAPL']:
        if holdlimit == 0:
            holdlimit -= 1000
            trades.append([prices.index[i], -1000])
        elif holdlimit == -1000:
            trades.append([prices.index[i], 0])
        else:
            holdlimit -= 2000
            trades.append([prices.index[i], -2000])
    else:
        trades.append([prices.index[i], 0])

df_trades = pd.DataFrame(trades, columns=["Date", "Shares"])
df_trades.set_index('Date',inplace=True)


# Get Optimal Portfolio
optimalportval = compute_portvals_single_symbol(df_trades,'AAPL', start_val=startval,commission=commission,impact=impact)
normedoptimalportval = optimalportval/optimalportval.ix[0]
cr = normedoptimalportval.iloc[-1, 0]/normedoptimalportval.iloc[0, 0] - 1
daily_returns = compute_daily_returns(normedoptimalportval)[1:]
adr = normedoptimalportval.iloc[:, 0].mean()
sddr = normedoptimalportval.iloc[:, 0].std()
sr = compute_sharpe_ratio(np.sqrt(252), adr, 0, sddr)

print("Cumulative Return of Optimal Portfolio: {}".format(cr))
print("Standard Deviation of Optimal Portfolio: {}".format(sddr))
print("Average Daily Return of Optimal Portfolio: {}".format(adr))
print("Sharpe Ratio of Benchmark: {}".format(sr))

Analysis: In order to understand upper bounds of performance a theoretically optimal strategy is developed by peaking into future on the in-sample data. To generate optimal trades, a logic was developed looking at next days stock price. If the difference between todays price and tomorrows price is positive i.e. todays price is greater than tomorrows price, then stock is sold. On the other hand, if the difference between todays price and tomorrows price is negative i.e. todays price is less than tomorrows price then stock is bought. Strategy was constrained by allowable positions of 1000 shares long, 1000 shares short and 0 shares, hence trading quantity was limited to 2000 shares. A logic was expanded to calculate quantity of shares to be traded based up the current holding quantity of the stock.

Above graph represents the implementation of theoretically optimal strategy for APPL for in sample dataset. As it can be observed from the chart and statistics, theoretically optimal strategy performs very well as compared to benchmark.

2.4 Manual Rule-Based Trader¶

This section implements a set of rules using the indicators discussed above and devise simple logic using indicators to enter and exit positions in the stock. This strategy leverages the technical indicators to generate trades. Following logic was developed to generate buy, sell or do nothing signals. Buy or sell is triggered when all three indicators meets the thresholds.

  • Buy stock if momentum is less than 0.05 and Bollingers Band percentage is less than 0.5 and price to SMA ratio is less than 0.1.
  • Sell the stock if momentum is greater than 0.05 and Bollingers Band percentage is greater than 0.5 and price to SMA ratio is greater than 0.1.
    Note that Buy, Sell or Do Nothing decision was also constrained by allowable positions of 1000 shares long, 1000 shares short and 0 shares, hence trading quantity was limited to 2000 shares. A logic was expanded to calculate quantity of shares to be traded based up the current holding quantity of the stock.
In [15]:
manstratport = pd.DataFrame(0, index = pricesnormed.index, columns = ["Shares"])

holdlimit = 0
for i in range(len(pricesnormed)-1):
    sma = dfsma.ix[i, 'SMA']
    pr2sma = dfsma.ix[i, 'Price/SMA']
    bbp = dfbb.ix[i, 'BBP']
    momentum = dfmomentum.ix[i, 'Momentum']

    if (momentum < 0.05) and (bbp < 0.5) and (pr2sma<0.1):
        if holdlimit == 0:
            holdlimit += 1000
            manstratport.ix[i,'Shares'] = +1000
        elif holdlimit == 1000:
            manstratport.ix[i,'Shares'] = 0
        else:
            holdlimit += 2000
            manstratport.ix[i,'Shares'] = +2000
    elif (momentum > 0.05) and (bbp > 0.5) and (pr2sma>0.1):
        if holdlimit == 0:
            holdlimit -= 1000
            manstratport.ix[i,'Shares'] = -1000
        elif holdlimit == -1000:
            manstratport.ix[i,'Shares'] = 0
        else:
            holdlimit -= 2000
            manstratport.ix[i,'Shares'] = -2000
    else:
        manstratport.ix[i,'Shares'] = 0
        
manstratportval = compute_portvals_single_symbol(manstratport,'AAPL', start_val=startval,commission=commission,impact=impact)
normedmanstratportval = manstratportval/manstratportval.ix[0]

cr = normedmanstratportval.iloc[-1, 0]/normedmanstratportval.iloc[0, 0] - 1
daily_returns = compute_daily_returns(normedmanstratportval)[1:]
adr = normedmanstratportval.iloc[:, 0].mean()
sddr = normedmanstratportval.iloc[:, 0].std()
sr = compute_sharpe_ratio(np.sqrt(252), adr, 0, sddr)

2.5 Q Learning Agent¶

Agent starts with an empty Q table, mapping states to values of actions. Q Learning agents has 3 actions viz, Buy, Sell or Do Nothing. Agent interacts with the environment, updates the Q Table with the tuple containing state, action, reward, new state. After that the agent decides which action to take.

                      commission=commission, verbose=True,
                      learner=learner)

Manual rule-based strategy on in-sample dataset does not consistently perform well whereas the performance on the out-sample was much better than benchmark performance. Rule based manual strategy causes higher price fluctuation in the In-Sample data as compared to Out-Sample data. This fluctuation in the In-Sample data can be attributed to more trades occurred in the In-Sample data.
